{{Nanotech}}
'''Nanosocialism''' refers generally to a set of [[economics|economic theories]] of [[social organization]] advocating [[State (polity)|state]] or [[collective ownership]] and administration of the [[research and development|research, development]] and use of [[nanotechnology]].
== Politics ==
{{further|Regulation of nanotechnology}}
Nanosocialism is a stance that favors [[participatory politics]] to guide [[state intervention]] in the effort to manage the transition to a [[society]] revolutionized by [[molecular nanotechnology]].<ref name="Berube 1996">{{cite journal| author = Berube, David| title = Nanosocialism| year = 1996 | url = http://www.cas.sc.edu/engl/faculty/berube/nanosoc.htm| accessdate=2007-01-30 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20061225060622/http://www.cas.sc.edu/engl/faculty/berube/nanosoc.htm <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2006-12-25}}</ref><ref name="Hughes 2001">{{cite journal| author = [[James Hughes (sociologist)|Hughes, James]]| title = Politics of Transhumanism| year = 2001 | url = http://www.changesurfer.com/Acad/TranshumPolitics.htm| accessdate=2007-01-26}}</ref>
"Nanosocialism" is a term coined by [[David M. Berube]], the associate director of Nanoscience and Technology Studies at the USC NanoCenter, who argues that nanotechnological projections need to be tempered by [[technorealism]] about the [[implications of nanotechnology]] in a [[technocapitalist]] society, but that its [[List of nanotechnology applications|applications]] also offer enormous opportunities for [[abundance (economics)|economic abundance]] and [[social progress]].<ref name="Berube 1996"/><ref name="Hughes 2001"/>
==In popular culture== {{unreferenced section|date=July 2012}} In the [[role-playing game]] ''[[Transhuman Space]]'', nanosocialism is described as a descendant of [[infosocialism]], in which [[intellectual property]] is [[nationalization|nationalized]] and freely distributed by the state. It is adopted by some developing nations to counter the hold corporations from wealthier nations have on [[copyright]]s and [[patent]]s. This fictional version of nanosocialism was coined by [[David L. Pulver]], the game's creator, who was unaware that the term had already been used by Berube.
